03/07/2020

This analysis is based on the data set provided by datacamp, and the time span considered for this is JAN 2020 - MAR 2020

Plotting Confirmed cases worldwide

ggplot(ccw, aes(date, cum_cases)) +
         geom_line() +
         ylab("Cumulative Confirmed Cases")

As shown in above plot the number of confirmed cases has increased constantly and reached around 200000 by march end. Although their was a dip in mid feb but then it continued increasing speedily.

Comparing China vs Rest of the World

confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world <- read_csv("confirmed_cases_china_vs_world.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   is_china = col_character(),
##   date = col_date(format = ""),
##   cases = col_double(),
##   cum_cases = col_double()
## )
glimpse(confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world)
## Observations: 112
## Variables: 4
## $ is_china  <chr> "China", "China", "China", "China", "China", "China", "Chin
## $ date      <date> 2020-01-22, 2020-01-23, 2020-01-24, 2020-01-25, 2020-01-26
## $ cases     <dbl> 548, 95, 277, 486, 669, 802, 2632, 578, 2054, 1661, 2089, 4
## $ cum_cases <dbl> 548, 643, 920, 1406, 2075, 2877, 5509, 6087, 8141, 9802, 11
plot_confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world <- ggplot(confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world) +
  geom_line(aes(date, cum_cases, group = is_china, color = is_china)) +
  ylab("Cumulative Cases Confirmed")

plot_confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world

From the above plot we can infer that initially there was a rise in number of cases in China , Covid-19 spread in China like a huge while rest of the world didnt even started getting affected at initial phase. Cases in China speeds up between Feb and March but then growth stopped and the slope became constant for China but for rest of the world it speeds up after march and grew exponentially. Around march 15th total number of cases outside China overtook the inside China cases, and this was the time when WHO declared it as a Pandemic.

A dataset provided by WHO , who_events, it states the different events like declaration of pandemic, etc.

who_events <- read.csv("who_events.csv")
who_events
##         date                             event
## 1 2020-01-30 Global health\nemergency declared
## 2 2020-02-13           China reporting\nchange
## 3 2020-03-11                Pandemic\ndeclared
who_events <-   tribble(~ date, ~ event,
                        
"2020-01-30", "Global health\nemergency declared",
  "2020-03-11", "Pandemic\ndeclared",
  "2020-02-13", "China reporting\nchange") %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(date))

plot_confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world +
geom_vline(aes(xintercept = date), data = who_events, linetype = "dashed") +

geom_text(aes(date,label = event), data = who_events, y = 1e5 )

According to the above plot we can see in the month of february the majority of cases were in China while after mid feb cases started sprouting in other countries, on 1st feb global health emergency was declared in China, and on on feb 15th the reporting changed. Cases started becoming constant in China while an increase was reported in other countries. Hence it was declared as a pandemic around mid march.

SCENARIO IN CHINA AFTER 15TH FEB

cases_in_china_after_15feb <- confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world %>%
  filter(is_china == "China", date >= "2020-02-15")
ggplot(cases_in_china_after_15feb, aes(date, cum_cases)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  ylab("Cumulative cases confirmed")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

From above plot we can see the scenario in China after 15th feb, it kept on increasing till march 9th and then started showing a dip. But we can observe that the growth is slower then linear which is a good sign, which shows that in China the spread has slowed down in late feb and early march.

SCENARIO IN REST OF THE WORLD - NON CHINA COUNTRIES

not_china <- confirmed_cases_china_vs_rest_world %>%
  filter(is_china == "Not China")

non_china_plot <- ggplot(not_china, aes(date, cum_cases)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  ylab("Cummulative cases confirmed")

non_china_plot
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Considering the situation in rest of the world initially there was no sign of virus or but after 15th feb number of cases grew exponentially.

non_china_plot +
    scale_y_log10()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

It seems a negative sign , that in rest of the world number of cases are increasing at an exponential rate.It may not be necessary that all countries outside China are affected , but we can study the extent of impact over other countries from the dataset provided confirmed cases by country.
